of mod droppings.

237
00:19:37,779 --> 00:19:39,539
Mod droppings?

238
00:19:39,698 --> 00:19:44,258
A mod is a being,
much like your skunk,
only far more potent.

239
00:19:46,872 --> 00:19:50,392
Uh, if it's such
a terrible experience,

240
00:19:50,625 --> 00:19:54,665
uh, how do you reproduce?

241
00:19:54,963 --> 00:19:57,483
As carefully as possible.

242
00:19:57,717 --> 00:19:59,557
What are you doing?

243
00:19:59,718 --> 00:20:03,398
Well, you just reminded me
of something I want to
include in my report.

244
00:20:03,639 --> 00:20:05,679
Your report.
Yes, it's our custom...

245
00:20:05,849 --> 00:20:08,529
to compile descriptions
of the various places
and people we encounter...

246
00:20:08,769 --> 00:20:10,609
throughout the galaxy.

247
00:20:15,320 --> 00:20:18,160
Morning, Betty.
Good morning, Prot.

248
00:20:18,365 --> 00:20:20,445
Morning, Navarro.
Hey, what's up, man?

249
00:20:20,657 --> 00:20:23,097
Mr. Friedman.
Morning, Maria.

250
00:20:23,327 --> 00:20:27,447
- I'm Vanessa.
- Just chill.

251
00:20:29,378 --> 00:20:30,898
Morning, Bess.

252
00:20:30,960 --> 00:20:31,800
Morning, Bess.

253
00:20:31,962 --> 00:20:36,922
She doesn't talk to anybody.
Afraid smoke will come out of
her mouth when she talks.

254
00:20:37,218 --> 00:20:39,938
Been here since
she was a little girl.
Burned her house down.

255
00:20:40,180 --> 00:20:43,060
Shouldn't play with matches.
Very dangerous.

256
00:20:43,308 --> 00:20:47,508
It was an electrical flare.
Why do you make up stories
like that?

257
00:20:47,812 --> 00:20:50,092
Ernie has a very powerful
imagination.

258
00:20:53,235 --> 00:20:55,635
Phil listen!

259
00:20:55,864 --> 00:21:00,544
Come on, Doris.
You gotta come out of
Your room sometime.

260
00:21:00,869 --> 00:21:02,789
Look what I brought
just for you.

261
00:21:04,416 --> 00:21:06,976
Pooh, pooh, pooh, pooh,
pooh, pooh, pooh, pooh.

262
00:21:07,210 --> 00:21:09,410
Do that again,
you go up to three.

263
00:21:11,422 --> 00:21:15,022
Her Royal Highness never,
ever comes out of her room.
Not even to eat.

264
00:21:15,259 --> 00:21:17,339
No wonder she's here.
I'm sick and tired
of this shit.

265
00:21:17,555 --> 00:21:20,395
Everyday, coming up here
and shooting food at me.
I hate this.

266
00:21:29,277 --> 00:21:31,957
The service here
is atrocious!

267
00:21:33,196 --> 00:21:37,236
Good morning, Mrs. Archer.
Doris.

268
00:21:39,830 --> 00:21:43,070
I wasn't expecting
any gentleman callers...

269
00:21:43,291 --> 00:21:45,451
until this afternoon.

270
00:21:45,627 --> 00:21:47,467
Excuse me.

271
00:22:01,311 --> 00:22:03,231
You have a place
set for two.

272
00:22:05,817 --> 00:22:10,537
Oh, yes. Um...
I'm expecting someone.

273
00:22:10,823 --> 00:22:12,743
How long
have you been waiting?

274
00:22:12,950 --> 00:22:14,830
Eleven years.

275
00:22:17,704 --> 00:22:21,944
For some around here
might...

276
00:22:22,208 --> 00:22:25,168
call that crazy,
but I prefer to call it...

277
00:22:25,421 --> 00:22:27,701
romantic.

278
00:22:27,924 --> 00:22:30,804
Romantic.
Like a, uh...

279
00:22:32,261 --> 00:22:34,821
waltz in the moonlight,
or a...

280
00:22:35,057 --> 00:22:37,657
candlelit dinner...

281
00:22:37,894 --> 00:22:40,174
or a sunset.
Oh, we have those.

282
00:22:40,356 --> 00:22:43,036
On K-PAX, we have two suns.

283
00:22:43,274 --> 00:22:47,114
They rlse together
only once every 200 years.

284
00:22:47,362 --> 00:22:49,282
And that is quite a sight.

285
00:22:52,701 --> 00:22:55,381
He most definitely
has a sensitivity
to white light,

286
00:22:55,578 --> 00:22:59,418
but I think
it's his range that
You'll find interesting.

287
00:22:59,668 --> 00:23:01,428
What am I looking at?

288
00:23:01,627 --> 00:23:05,507
He can detect light
at a wavelength of up to
300 to 400 angstroms.

289
00:23:06,924 --> 00:23:09,044
Ultraviolet.

290
00:23:09,264 --> 00:23:12,024
Of course,
Prot's explanation is that...

291
00:23:12,223 --> 00:23:16,423
due to his planet's
peculiar quality of light
caused by its two suns,

292
00:23:16,686 --> 00:23:21,926
K-PAXians are used to
light conditions much like
our twilight most of the time.

293
00:23:22,275 --> 00:23:24,155
W-Wait a minute.
Chuck, I didn't think...

294
00:23:24,362 --> 00:23:26,242
human beings could see
ultraviolet light.

295
00:23:26,405 --> 00:23:28,165
We can't.

296
00:23:45,886 --> 00:23:47,686
Good morning, Joyce.

297
00:23:47,889 --> 00:23:51,049
That's a lovely configuration
You're wearing today.
Thank you.

298
00:23:52,851 --> 00:23:54,651
Macy's.
Come in.

299
00:24:06,866 --> 00:24:08,866
This is so much better.

300
00:24:10,621 --> 00:24:12,461
It's a lot like home.

301
00:24:26,013 --> 00:24:28,413
Well, uh, Prot,

302
00:24:28,600 --> 00:24:31,360
I was hoping you'd tell me
more about home.

303
00:24:33,938 --> 00:24:35,738
Well, what would you
like to know?

304
00:24:37,109 --> 00:24:39,949
Well, uh, do you, um,

305
00:24:41,280 --> 00:24:44,520
do you have a family
on K-PAX?

306
00:24:44,782 --> 00:24:47,462
It doesn't work on K-PAX
the same way it works
here, Mark.

307
00:24:47,662 --> 00:24:50,782
On K-PAX, we don't
have families in the way
that you think of them.

308
00:24:50,999 --> 00:24:55,279
In fact, a family would be
a non sequitur on our planet,
as it would on most others.

309
00:24:56,674 --> 00:24:58,834
In other words, um,

310
00:24:59,009 --> 00:25:03,569
You, uh, you never knew
Your parents.

311
00:25:03,847 --> 00:25:07,967
On K-PAX, children are not
raised by their biological
parents, Mark, but by everyone.

312
00:25:08,227 --> 00:25:11,347
They circulate among us,
learning from one
and then another.

313
00:25:11,606 --> 00:25:14,366
Do you have a child?
No.

314
00:25:16,235 --> 00:25:19,035
Do you have a wife waiting
back for you on K-PAX?

315
00:25:19,239 --> 00:25:21,079
Mark. Mark. Mark.

316
00:25:23,616 --> 00:25:27,136
You are not really listening
to what I'm saying to you,
are you?

317
00:25:29,502 --> 00:25:31,302
We do not have marriage
on K-PAX.

318
00:25:31,504 --> 00:25:33,744
There are no wives.
There are no husbands.

319
00:25:33,963 --> 00:25:36,523
There are no families.

320
00:25:40,180 --> 00:25:43,700
I see. So, um,

321
00:25:43,975 --> 00:25:47,735
what about...
societal structure?

322
00:25:48,020 --> 00:25:50,420
Government.
No, there's
no need for one.

323
00:25:50,649 --> 00:25:54,529
- You have no laws?
- No laws. No lawyers.

324
00:25:54,818 --> 00:25:57,418
How do you know
right from wrong?

325
00:25:57,656 --> 00:26:01,256
Every being
in the universe knows
right from wrong, Mark.

326
00:26:04,495 --> 00:26:07,295
But what if--

327
00:26:07,543 --> 00:26:10,823
if someone did do
something wrong--

328
00:26:11,048 --> 00:26:15,008
committed murder or rape--

329
00:26:15,301 --> 00:26:17,261
how would you punish them?

330
00:26:20,724 --> 00:26:23,044
Let me tell you
something, Mark.

331
00:26:23,225 --> 00:26:25,745
You humans, most of you,

332
00:26:25,938 --> 00:26:28,578
subscribe to this policy
of "an eye for an eye,

333
00:26:28,773 --> 00:26:31,093
a life for a life,"
which is known
throughout the universe...

334
00:26:31,277 --> 00:26:33,117
for its stupidity.

335
00:26:33,278 --> 00:26:35,718
Even your Buddha and your Christ
had quite a different vision,

336
00:26:35,906 --> 00:26:39,506
but nobody's paid much attention
to them, not even the Buddhists
or the Christians.

337
00:26:41,289 --> 00:26:44,729
You humans,

338
00:26:45,001 --> 00:26:48,281
sometimes it's hard to imagine
how you've made it this far.

339
00:26:59,307 --> 00:27:01,787
Josh, be careful.

340
00:27:03,353 --> 00:27:05,353
Okay, kids. Let's go.
The hot dogs are ready.

341
00:27:09,486 --> 00:27:12,166
Hey. Where were you
just now?

342
00:27:14,073 --> 00:27:15,873
Come on.
Okay.

343
00:27:17,204 --> 00:27:21,084
Hey, kids, come on.
Wash up.

344
00:27:21,334 --> 00:27:22,934
Okay!

345
00:27:24,544 --> 00:27:27,824
Josh. Now come on,
quit teasing the dog.

346
00:27:28,049 --> 00:27:30,209
Josh, let's go.
Settle down now.

347
00:27:30,426 --> 00:27:33,946
- Here we are.
- Oh, park that right here.

348
00:27:35,555 --> 00:27:37,395
Boy,
that looks terrific.
That looks great.

349
00:27:37,558 --> 00:27:39,198
Steve, how was, uh,
how was your trip
up from Princeton?

350
00:27:39,268 --> 00:27:41,588
Steve, how was, uh,
how was your trip
up from Princeton?

351
00:27:41,813 --> 00:27:45,333
Not too bad.
We even stopped by
to see Michael.

352
00:27:45,608 --> 00:27:47,688
Oh, that was
nice of you, Sis.

353
00:27:47,902 --> 00:27:49,782
Quite a detour
for you guys.

354
00:27:49,988 --> 00:27:52,108
Well, it was his birthday.

355
00:27:52,326 --> 00:27:54,686
I know it was his birthday.

356
00:27:54,869 --> 00:27:57,549
I sent him a card
and a nice, uh,

357
00:27:57,791 --> 00:27:59,591
a nice, big check
as usual.

358
00:27:59,793 --> 00:28:02,673
It wouldn't kill you
to pick up the phone
every once in a while...

359
00:28:02,877 --> 00:28:04,717
and talk to your own son.

360
00:28:04,880 --> 00:28:08,680
Thank you, Abby.
You wanna pass
the potato salad, please?

361
00:28:09,928 --> 00:28:11,768
There you go.

362
00:28:11,930 --> 00:28:15,210
By the way, I put him
through Dartmouth. He knows
how to pick up a phone too.

363
00:28:15,474 --> 00:28:18,714
I'm thinking of inviting him
for Christmas.
Oh, great.

364
00:28:18,978 --> 00:28:22,338
He spends Christmas
with his mother.

365
00:28:22,608 --> 00:28:25,728
He won't come here.
How do you know? When was
the last time you asked him?

366
00:28:25,987 --> 00:28:28,147
Am I on the couch here,
or what?

367
00:28:28,364 --> 00:28:30,804
You want a beer?
Please and thank you.

368
00:28:31,035 --> 00:28:32,835
You want some more?
Can I have corn, darling?

369
00:28:38,209 --> 00:28:40,729
Steve, I, uh,

370
00:28:40,963 --> 00:28:43,283
I have a rather unusual
favor to ask you.

371
00:28:43,506 --> 00:28:45,946
What can I do you for,
Dr. "P''?
Well, I have a patient.

372
00:28:46,175 --> 00:28:48,895
Sit down. I have
this patient, who, uh,

373
00:28:49,096 --> 00:28:50,936
seems to know quite
a bit about your field.

374
00:28:51,098 --> 00:28:53,298
A patient
who's an astronomer?

375
00:28:53,516 --> 00:28:56,076
So, tell me about
this patient of yours.

376
00:28:56,311 --> 00:29:01,151
Well, he, uh, he claims
to come from a planet
he calls K-PAX.

377
00:29:01,444 --> 00:29:03,804
What kind of name
is that?
K-PAX?

378
00:29:04,029 --> 00:29:09,149
He says it's a thousand
light-years away, near
the constellation Lyra.

379
00:29:09,452 --> 00:29:12,772
Uh-huh. Bighead?
Green? About this high?

380
00:29:12,998 --> 00:29:15,038
Yeah, I think
I know the guy.

381
00:29:15,249 --> 00:29:17,969
No, he's, uh,
he's very convincing.

382
00:29:22,009 --> 00:29:25,729
I mean, of course,
he's, uh, he's human.

383
00:29:25,969 --> 00:29:27,809
It’s just that he's, um,

384
00:29:27,971 --> 00:29:31,971
well, he's-he's the most
convincing delusional
I've ever come across.

385
00:29:32,268 --> 00:29:36,588
If I can prove to him
that this K-PAX is just
a figment of his imagination,

386
00:29:36,899 --> 00:29:39,939
then maybe I can find out
who he really is.

387
00:29:40,153 --> 00:29:42,953
Well, sure.
I can give you...

388
00:29:43,158 --> 00:29:45,518
a whole list of questions
to ask your fella.
Wonderful.

389
00:29:47,786 --> 00:29:50,186
All his books and papers
and everything...

390
00:29:50,373 --> 00:29:55,133
are spread all over the desk
like always, but he's
just sitting there.

391
00:29:55,460 --> 00:29:57,260
Someone change
his medication?

392
00:29:57,464 --> 00:30:01,144
I gave him his usual,
Anafronil, 250 milligrams.

393
00:30:05,888 --> 00:30:08,728
Hmm. Well, something's
wrong with him.

394
00:30:08,975 --> 00:30:13,735
An obsessive-compulsive
doesn't just sit there
looking out the window.

395
00:30:22,408 --> 00:30:24,248
Howie?

396
00:30:29,248 --> 00:30:31,568
Good morning,
Dr. Powell.

397
00:30:31,793 --> 00:30:35,993
Good morning.
But are you looking
for something?

398
00:30:36,255 --> 00:30:38,095
Bluebird.

399
00:30:38,258 --> 00:30:40,218
The bluebird?

400
00:30:40,427 --> 00:30:42,267
The bluebird of happiness.

401
00:30:44,847 --> 00:30:47,687
Prot told me to find
the bluebird of happiness.

402
00:30:47,895 --> 00:30:50,455
Prot told you.

403
00:30:50,690 --> 00:30:52,490
It's a task.

404
00:30:52,692 --> 00:30:54,492
The first of three.

405
00:30:56,528 --> 00:30:59,248
I don't know what
the other two are yet.

406
00:30:59,491 --> 00:31:02,051
He'll tell me.

407
00:31:02,244 --> 00:31:06,084
If I complete all three,

408
00:31:06,372 --> 00:31:08,172
I'll be cured.

409
00:31:20,221 --> 00:31:23,061
There.
Maintain your breathing.

410
00:31:23,310 --> 00:31:25,630
That's it.
Now you see?

411
00:31:25,852 --> 00:31:28,172
There are none of
these ammonia particles
that you're so worried about.

412
00:31:28,397 --> 00:31:31,277
In the first place,
I would be able to see them.
Good morning, Sal.

413
00:31:31,526 --> 00:31:33,326
And I don't.
Good morning, Dr. Stinky.

414
00:31:33,529 --> 00:31:35,929
Ringed monkey, 7:00.

415
00:31:40,578 --> 00:31:42,378
Take a bath.
Take a bath.

416
00:31:42,580 --> 00:31:45,900
Ernie, could you excuse us
for a moment, please?
Mm-hmm.

417
00:31:46,166 --> 00:31:48,006
Good to, uh,
see you outside, Ernie.

418
00:31:48,169 --> 00:31:51,249
Thank you.
Oh, Ernie, you stink.

419
00:31:51,464 --> 00:31:54,624
Prot, it's one thing
to take an interest
in your fellow patients.

420
00:31:54,883 --> 00:31:57,763
It's quite another
to make them think
that you can cure them.

421
00:31:57,972 --> 00:31:59,852
You seem overly upset,
Mark.

422
00:32:00,058 --> 00:32:03,418
To borrow a phrase from Navarro,
You need to chill.

423
00:32:03,688 --> 00:32:06,768
For your information,
all beings have the capacity
to cure themselves, Mark.

424
00:32:06,981 --> 00:32:09,581
This is something
we've known on K-PAX
for millions of years.

425
00:32:09,777 --> 00:32:13,737
Listen to me.
On this planet,
I'm a doctor, you're a patient.

426
00:32:14,032 --> 00:32:17,672
Doctor. Patient.
Curious human distinction.

427
00:32:17,952 --> 00:32:20,752
It's not your job
to cure Howie.

428
00:32:20,955 --> 00:32:23,835
Or Ernie or Maria
or anyone else.
It's mine.

429
00:32:24,042 --> 00:32:26,042
Then why haven't
You cured them yet?

430
00:32:28,296 --> 00:32:32,656
Oh, by the way,
here are the answers
to the questions you asked me.

431
00:32:35,764 --> 00:32:37,564
I hope they meet
Your satisfaction.

432
00:32:52,365 --> 00:32:54,205
I don't know what to say, Mark.

433
00:32:54,366 --> 00:32:57,926
I mean, this is--
this is pretty wild stuff.

434
00:32:58,162 --> 00:33:02,002
Gibberish, huh?
Well, not exactly.

435
00:33:02,293 --> 00:33:04,453
I mean, see,

436
00:33:04,668 --> 00:33:07,388
Your patient indicates
his planet, K-PAX,

437
00:33:07,632 --> 00:33:11,472
orbitingan eclipsing
binary star system--
Agape and Satori.

438
00:33:11,721 --> 00:33:14,361
Yeah.
Near the Constellation Lyra.

439
00:33:14,597 --> 00:33:16,597
He could have
looked that up, right?

440
00:33:17,852 --> 00:33:20,732
That's the funny thing, Mark.
Not really.

441
00:33:20,981 --> 00:33:24,701
I mean, except for my boss,
Duncan Flynn,

442
00:33:24,943 --> 00:33:27,703
one of the foremost
astrophysicists in the world...

443
00:33:27,904 --> 00:33:32,064
and maybe two or three
of his colleagues,

444
00:33:32,368 --> 00:33:35,488
nobody knows much about
the possibility of planets
in this star system yet.

445
00:33:35,703 --> 00:33:38,063
It hasn't even been reported
in any journals.

446
00:33:39,416 --> 00:33:41,936
Tell me, honestly,

447
00:33:42,172 --> 00:33:44,092
did Duncan put you
up to this?

448
00:33:44,257 --> 00:33:46,777
You know--
You know, like a joke?

449
00:33:47,009 --> 00:33:50,529
No. It's no joke, Steve.

450
00:33:50,806 --> 00:33:52,926
Uh, tell me,

451
00:33:53,142 --> 00:33:56,262
do you know of any missing
astrophysicists?

452
00:33:56,519 --> 00:33:59,839
Can't say I do.

453
00:34:00,065 --> 00:34:03,545
But there's one or two
around here who'd sure like
to meet this fella of yours.

454
00:34:03,779 --> 00:34:06,179
Thanks a lot, Steve.
I sure appreciate it.

455
00:34:12,830 --> 00:34:15,030
But unlike you humans,
the reproductive process...

456
00:34:15,247 --> 00:34:17,087
is an unpleasant one for us.
Start again.

457
00:34:17,207 --> 00:34:20,847
What way is it unpleasant?

458
00:34:21,006 --> 00:34:22,846
It's a pain--

459
00:34:32,559 --> 00:34:36,799
Good. Not too fast.
Okay.

460
00:36:46,791 --> 00:36:48,911
So, this is
Your neighborhood, huh?

461
00:36:57,970 --> 00:37:00,850
Hello, gentlemen.
Sure appreciate you
meeting with us.

462
00:37:01,098 --> 00:37:04,138
Thank you, Dr. Powell.
We'd like to get to the bottom
of this just as much as you.

463
00:37:04,395 --> 00:37:08,315
Thank you, Doctor.
Great. Let me introduce
You to Prot.

464
00:37:10,608 --> 00:37:13,488
It's a pleasure
to meet you, Prot.
I'm Dr. Becker.

465
00:37:13,698 --> 00:37:16,138
This is Dr. Flynn.

466
00:37:16,323 --> 00:37:18,683
Drs. Patel and Hessler.

467
00:37:20,538 --> 00:37:24,898
Doctor. Doctor.
Doctor. Doctor.

468
00:37:26,460 --> 00:37:28,580
How many doctors
are there on this planet?

469
00:37:45,815 --> 00:37:49,215
Here, Prot.
Have a seat.

470
00:37:49,486 --> 00:37:52,486
"Have a seat.''
Oh, shit!

471
00:37:54,909 --> 00:37:57,029
Feel at home?

